Accuracy Comparison.
To verify the effectiveness of our FL approach, FedMRI, in multi-institutional collaboration, we compare it with various state-of-the-art FL algorithms. For fair comparison, we retrain them on MR data and report their optimal results. For FedProx, we tune its hyperparameter Î¼ğœ‡\mu within {0.001,0.01,0.1,1}0.0010.010.11\{0.001,0.01,0.1,1\} and report the best result at 0.010.010.01. For other methods, we use their default parameters and retrain them on the same datasets. All the compared methods are trained over 707070 communication rounds with 101010 local epochs each, and they all converge at round 707070 (see section Â§4). TableÂ 1 shows the reconstruction results of all methods under Scenario 1, which employs 1D uniform sampling with 3Ã—\times acceleration. We use the paired Studentâ€™s t-test to evaluate the significant difference between the two methods. P<ğ‘ƒabsentP< 0.001 was considered as a statistically significant level. Our FedMRI is superior to all the other methods in both PSNR and SSIM. In particular, on small datasets, such as SMS and uMR, our method improves the PSNR results of FedAvg from 25.2525.2525.25 dB and 21.0921.0921.09 dB to 39.76 dB and 38.2 dB, respectively. However, Transfer-site has the lowest results because it cannot solve the non-IID problem. The model can only concentrate on the current client, and the previous model will be forgotten after transfer to other clients. More importantly, even compared with the methods that also used KI-Net as the client model, our FedMRI is still significantly higher than them. This demonstrates that the client update mechanism (see Eq.Â (7).) of our FedMRI can effectively remove the domain shift in the non-IID datasets. The distributed training on data from multiple institutions without compromising privacy can solve the dependence of traditional deep learning on the collection of big data.

Robustness to a Higher Domain-Shift Setting.
To further evaluate the robustness of our method, we record the results of each client under different sampling patterns and accelerations in TableÂ 2. Considering that various hospital scanners use different scanners, we employ different undersampling patterns, e.g., 1D uniform 3Ã—\times, 1D Cartesian 5Ã—\times, 2D radial 4Ã—\times, and 2D random 6Ã—\times, to set up Scenario 2. As expected, our method achieves better results under a higher domain shift. In contrast, the FedAvg and MRI multi-institutional collaboration method, FL-MRCM, performs worse under this scenario. Compared with other methods, FedMRI is most robust because it can balance the learning of local and global representations, ensuring that the client learns unique client-specific properties.

Weighted Contrastive Regularization:
Although we have shared the weight Î˜GeszsuperscriptsubscriptÎ˜superscriptsubscriptğºğ‘’ğ‘ ğ‘§\Theta_{G_{e}^{s}}^{z} to the server to find the generalized representation among the clients, there is always an offset between Î˜GezsuperscriptsubscriptÎ˜subscriptğºğ‘’ğ‘§\Theta_{G_{e}}^{z} and Î˜GeszsuperscriptsubscriptÎ˜superscriptsubscriptğºğ‘’ğ‘ ğ‘§\Theta_{G_{e}^{s}}^{z} during iterative optimization, mainly caused by the domain shift during local optimization. To further correct the local updates and provide the model with global recognition ability, we introduce weighted contrastive regularization between the local and global encoders to force Gessuperscriptsubscriptğºğ‘’ğ‘ {G_{e}^{s}} to learn a stronger generalized representation. Different to construct positive and negative pairs on data, we directly regularize the update direction on the network parameters, which is different from traditional contrastive learning. This enables the gradient updates to be corrected more directly, without relying on a large batch sizeÂ [51]. Our experimental results also support this, as shown in TableÂ 4.

In this section, we first investigate the crucial components in our method, e.g., the shared part of the local client (Gekssuperscriptsubscriptğºsubscriptğ‘’ğ‘˜ğ‘ G_{e_{k}}^{s}, Gdkssuperscriptsubscriptğºsubscriptğ‘‘ğ‘˜ğ‘ G_{d_{k}}^{s}, Geissuperscriptsubscriptğºsubscriptğ‘’ğ‘–ğ‘ G_{e_{i}}^{s} and Gdissuperscriptsubscriptğºsubscriptğ‘‘ğ‘–ğ‘ G_{d_{i}}^{s}), and weighted contrastive regularization. For comparison, we build two baselines, â„³1subscriptâ„³1\mathcal{M}_{1} and â„³2subscriptâ„³2\mathcal{M}_{2}, which represent our model without the partially shared network and weighted contrastive regularization respectively. As shown in TableÂ 4, we conduct tests under Scenario 2. â„³1subscriptâ„³1\mathcal{M}_{1} performs the worst, indicating that partially sharing the representation makes it possible to train on different clients with different domains. Since the weighted contrastive regularization term corrects the offsets of local client updates, the generalized representation learned by â„³2subscriptâ„³2\mathcal{M}_{2} is not optimal when this term is lost. In addition, we also investigate the effect of using traditional contrastive learning (see â„³3subscriptâ„³3\mathcal{M}_{3}), which adopts the positive and negative feature pairs, as mentioned inÂ [57]. As can be seen, â„³3subscriptâ„³3\mathcal{M}_{3} is far inferior to directly imposing contrastive regularization on the parameters, which can directly correct the gradient updates and does not depend on a large batch size. Our FedMRI obtains the best results thanks to its two crucial parts, proving its strong ability in removing the domain shift. To evaluate the effectiveness of our partial shared mechanism in the hybrid domain, we record the results of â„³4subscriptâ„³4\mathcal{M}_{4} that only performed on the image domain. As can be seen from these results, our method still obtains high accuracy on the single domain demonstrating that our specificity-preserving mechanism can help the MR image reconstruction in multi-institution joint training.
